---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Scorecard from '../components/Scorecard.astro';
import ConvergenceTimeline from '../components/ConvergenceTimeline.astro';
---

<Base
  active="landscape"
  title="The landscape — where storytree fits, honestly"
  description="A neutral, primary-sourced survey of the AI-coding-agent field against storytree's three surfaces: a library, a code map, and a work-board. Who built what, what might be new, and the honest case that it's mostly renaming."
>
  <!-- intro -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">The landscape</p>
      <h1>Are we onto something — or just renaming it?</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Honesty is the whole point of this project, so here's the uncomfortable version: storytree
        didn't invent any of its parts. The interesting question is whether putting them together is a
        real advance or a tidy rename. We went and surveyed the field to find out — and we'll show you
        the case against, not just the case for.
      </p>
      <p>
        The binding constraint on an AI&nbsp;coding agent isn't raw intelligence. It's the
        <strong>context window</strong> and the lack of memory between sessions — an agent works inside a
        finite attention budget, and when the session ends it forgets. The instinct is to give it
        <em>more</em>: a bigger window, the whole repo pasted in. The most thoughtful practitioners say
        that's backwards. The better move is to <strong>manage attention, not expand it</strong> — give
        the agent a map it reads on demand and writes back to, so state lives outside the prompt and
        survives the session.
      </p>
      <p>
        storytree splits that map into <strong>three surfaces</strong>: a
        <strong>library</strong> (what's known — decisions, definitions, guidance), a
        <strong>code map</strong> (what the system is — the codebase as an authored DAG), and a
        <strong>work-board</strong> (what's being done — a dependency-aware task tier). The survey below
        tests that model against what everyone else has actually shipped, scored from primary sources.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the scorecard -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">The survey</p>
      <h2>Everyone's built a piece. We looked for who'd built all three.</h2>
      <p>
        Each cohort builds one axis and stops. The code-map cohort — Aider's repo map, CodeGraph,
        Augment, Cody — gives an agent a view of the code and nothing else. The library cohort —
        Anthropic's Skills and memory, Letta's memory blocks — builds the knowledge tier and no code map.
        Steve Yegge's Beads and Gas&nbsp;Town land squarely on the work-board. Geoffrey Huntley's loom has
        the raw components — thread search, a docs publisher, VCS tooling — but none is presented as an
        integrated, agent-facing surface. Scored against the three surfaces, it looks like this:
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <Scorecard />
    </div>
    <div class="wrap prose legend-note">
      <p class="muted">
        A caution we take seriously: this is the <em>surveyed sources at one date</em>. Several named
        players — Cursor, Cline, Devin, Factory, OpenHands, Windsurf — produced no verified claims in
        this pass and are deliberately left off the board. Absence of evidence isn't evidence of absence;
        any of them could be building the triad unobserved here.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- what might be new -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">What might be new</p>
      <h2>Two things we didn't find anyone else doing.</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>One: the unification.</strong> No tool we surveyed builds all three surfaces as one
        coherent model. That's it — not a capability nobody else <em>could</em> build, just a combination
        we didn't find anyone holding. When independent teams keep arriving at the same primitives, the
        primitives are probably right; storytree's bet is that you arrive faster if you draw the whole
        map at once instead of one wall at a time.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Two: the altitude.</strong> The code-map tools operate at <em>symbol altitude</em> — a
        bottom-up mirror of the code as written, extracted mechanically from source. The map reflects the
        code; change the code and it re-mirrors. storytree's code map is the other way around: it's
        authored top-down <em>as intent</em>, and the code has to satisfy <em>it</em>. A
        <strong>story</strong> is the size of a service; a <strong>capability</strong> is an organ inside
        it. Spec-driven tools like Spec&nbsp;Kit and Kiro do author intent top-down too — they're the
        closest neighbours here — but they tend to flatten it into per-feature checklists that are thrown
        away when the feature ships, rather than a standing, architectural map that outlives any one task.
      </p>
      <p class="muted">
        Both claims are narrow on purpose. “Distinctive” here means “not found in this survey” — not
        “proven novel.” We'd rather under-claim and be right.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the field converged -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">The field converged</p>
      <h2>Smart people walked toward these surfaces from different directions.</h2>
      <p>
        The strongest evidence that the individual pieces are sound is that the field built them
        independently, piece by piece, without coordinating. Convergent evolution is a useful signal.
        Here's the dated version — every entry traces to a primary source, and the soft dates are flagged.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <ConvergenceTimeline />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- the honest box -->
  <section class="section" id="caveats">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="honest">
        <div class="honest__inner">
          <p class="eyebrow">The skeptical read</p>
          <h2>The strongest argument that this is nothing.</h2>
          <p class="lede">
            Task trackers, docs-and-memory tiers, and VCS-backed code views already exist — in
            unintegrated form. Maybe storytree just labels and arranges primitives that Beads, Skills, and
            Aider already shipped, and the “unification” is a presentation choice, not a capability. On
            that reading, the contribution is mostly <em>naming</em>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The honest counter is narrow: the three surfaces are a pattern the field independently
            converged on; no surveyed tool unifies all three; and the authored, architecture-altitude
            code map is a genuinely different object from the bottom-up mirrors everyone else built.
            Whether that adds up to a real advance or a tidy rename is the open question — and it's more
            useful to leave it open than to answer it louder than the evidence allows.
          </p>

          <div class="honest__caveats">
            <h3>The caveats, on the table</h3>
            <ul class="caveats">
              <li>
                <strong>It's a point-in-time snapshot.</strong> The sources span roughly 2023–mid&nbsp;2026
                and the fast movers move fast. “No one unifies all three” is a finding about these sources
                at this date, not a guarantee about the field.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>The mappings are our framing.</strong> Casting Beads as a work-board, Skills as a
                library, or Aider's repo map as a code map is our interpretation. None of these projects
                describes itself in storytree's “three surfaces” language.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>There are coverage gaps.</strong> Several known tools produced no verified claims
                this pass and are off the board. Absence of evidence is not evidence of absence.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Some internals are genuinely contested.</strong> The embedding-vs-graph reading of
                Augment and Cody was challenged during verification, so the code-map cohort shouldn't be
                read as a uniform family of structural graphs — we mark the surface, not the mechanism.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>“Distinctive” ≠ “first.”</strong> Where we call the unification or the altitude
                distinctive, that's a statement about what this survey did and didn't surface — not a
                claim of first-ever invention.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p class="honest__src">
            The marks above are scored from primary sources, linked inline throughout this page and
            consolidated from three adversarially-verified research passes (Jun&nbsp;2026). Where a claim
            was refuted in verification — including two “agent momentum” citations — we dropped it rather
            than dress it up.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- cta -->
  <section class="section--tight">
    <div class="wrap prose cta-card">
      <h2>That's the honest landscape.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        If the bet makes sense to you — or if you think it's a rename and want to say so — that's exactly
        the kind of conversation this is built for.
      </p>
      <div class="hero__cta">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="/how-it-works/">See how the three fit together →</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="/get-involved/">Get involved</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .legend-note { margin-top: 1rem; }
  .legend-note p { font-size: 0.92rem; margin: 0; }
  em { font-style: italic; }

  .honest {
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--line-strong);
    border-left: 5px solid var(--amber);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow);
  }
  .honest__inner { padding: clamp(1.6rem, 4vw, 2.8rem); max-width: 48rem; }
  .honest .eyebrow { color: var(--amber); }
  .honest__caveats { margin-top: 1.6rem; padding-top: 1.4rem; border-top: 1px dashed var(--line-strong); }
  .honest__caveats h3 { margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }
  .caveats { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; display: grid; gap: 0.85rem; }
  .caveats li {
    position: relative; padding-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--ink-soft); font-size: 0.96rem;
  }
  .caveats li::before {
    content: ""; position: absolute; left: 0; top: 0.62em; width: 0.5rem; height: 0.5rem;
    border-radius: 999px; background: var(--amber-soft); box-shadow: inset 0 0 0 2px var(--amber);
  }
  .caveats strong { color: var(--ink); }
  .honest__src {
    margin: 1.6rem 0 0; padding-top: 1.2rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    font-size: 0.88rem; color: var(--ink-faint);
  }

  .cta-card { text-align: center; max-width: 40rem; }
  .cta-card .hero__cta { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.7rem; margin-top: 1.4rem; justify-content: center; }
</style>
